loads three main matrices:

    Gdrug_mu → drug × gene average perturbation
    Gdrug_sigma → variability of that perturbation
    Gadr → ADR × gene associations
    The ADR matrix is sparse and converted to dense for faster computation. 

Construct Effective Drug–Gene Signal
    The model builds an effective perturbation signal:
        Gdrug_eff = Gdrug_mu / (Gdrug_sigma + eps)
    This emphasizes strong consistent gene perturbations while downweighting noisy ones.

Then each gene feature is standardized (z-score normalization): (feature − mean) / std

This ensures all genes are on comparable scales for training.
    Final shapes printed:
    drug × gene
    ADR × gene

Load Drug–ADR Ground Truth (SIDER): The file sider_lincs_common_clean_FINAL.csv contains known drug–ADR pairs.

Two index mapping files are used:
    drug_index.csv
    adr_index.csv

converts every valid row into: (d, a) = (drug_index, adr_index)- These pairs represent positive training examples.
    80% train drugs
    10% validation drugs
    10% test drugs

All ADR pairs for a drug go into the same split.=> This prevents information leakage.

Feature Construction: For each drug–ADR pair a 574-dimensional feature vector is created.
Feature: interaction = drug_gene_vector × adr_gene_mask

    drug_gene_vector → effect of drug on genes
    adr_gene_mask → genes associated with ADR
    Element-wise multiplication captures which genes are both: perturbed by the drug, linked to the ADR

This becomes the input feature vector.

Dataset with Negative Sampling
The dataset returns:
    1 positive ADR for the drug
    10 randomly sampled negative ADRs

Negative ADRs are chosen such that: (drug, adr) is not a known positive.
This converts the problem into a ranking task.

Returned tensors:
    positive feature vector
    negative feature vectors

Neural Network Model: A small MLP predicts a score for a drug–ADR interaction.

Architecture: 574 → 256 → 128 → 1

Layers: Linear, ReLU, Dropout, Linear, ReLU, Linear

Output = interaction score.
Higher score → model believes the drug causes that ADR.

Training Objective (BPR Ranking Loss)
Training uses a pairwise ranking objective.

For each positive ADR and negative ADR: score_pos − score_neg

Loss: softplus(−(score_pos − score_neg))

Meaning: The model learns to make score_pos > score_neg.

Per batch:
    Compute positive scores
    Compute negative scores
    Apply BPR loss
    Backpropagation
    Gradient clipping for stability

Validation is run every 2 epochs using Recall@50 and Mean Percentile Rank.

Random ranking gives approximately:
    Recall@10 ≈ 0.0027
    Recall@50 ≈ 0.0137

